The **Game of Two Stacks** problem (commonly seen on **HackerRank**) asks us to remove the maximum number of elements from two stacks without 
the total sum exceeding a given limit `x`. We can only remove elements from the **top** of each stack, so the order of elements cannot be changed. 
The optimal approach avoids checking every possible combination and instead uses a **two-pointer (greedy) strategy**. 
First, we remove elements from **stack A** one by one until adding the next element would exceed `x`. This gives an initial count.
Then we start taking elements from **stack B**.
Whenever adding an element from B causes the sum to exceed `x`, 
we remove elements from A (moving the pointer backward) until the sum becomes valid again. After each adjustment,
we update the maximum number of removed elements (`i + j`). Because each element of both stacks is visited at most once,
the time complexity is **O(n + m)** where `n` and `m` are the sizes of the two stacks.
This method is efficient and avoids the exponential time complexity of the recursive approach.
